The following code attempts to implement an undo system using copy, but it has a bug: it uses shallow copy so nested mutations aren't properly undone. Fix it.

```python
import copy

class UndoableState:
    def __init__(self, data: dict):
        self._data = data
        self._history = []

    def set(self, key, value):
        self._history.append(copy.copy(self._data))  # BUG: shallow copy
        self._data[key] = value

    def undo(self):
        if self._history:
            self._data = self._history.pop()
        else:
            raise IndexError('Nothing to undo')

    def get(self, key, default=None):
        return self._data.get(key, default)

    @property
    def data(self):
        return dict(self._data)
```

Fix it so nested dict/list mutations are properly tracked in history.

The following Python descriptor is supposed to enforce type checking on class attributes, but it has a critical bug: all instances share the same value because the descriptor stores the value on itself, not on the instance. Fix it.

```python
class TypeChecked:
    def __init__(self, name, expected_type):
        self.name = name
        self.expected_type = expected_type
        self.value = None  # BUG: shared across all instances

    def __get__(self, obj, objtype=None):
        if obj is None:
            return self
        return self.value  # Returns same value for all instances!

    def __set__(self, obj, value):
        if not isinstance(value, self.expected_type):
            raise TypeError(f'{self.name} must be {self.expected_type.__name__}, got {type(value).__name__}')
        self.value = value  # Stores on descriptor, not instance

class Person:
    name = TypeChecked('name', str)
    age = TypeChecked('age', int)

    def __init__(self, name, age):
        self.name = name
        self.age = age
```

Fix it so each instance has its own values. The standard pattern is to store in `obj.__dict__`.

